"Dee Boersma P.","Population trends of the Galapagos Penguin: Impacts of El Nino and La Nina",1998,"Condor","100","2",,"245","253",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0344936727&partnerID=40&md5=5e3945e401373a71c5bb70f89292ccc0","Department of Zoology, University of Washington, Seattle, WA 98195-1800, United States","Dee Boersma, P., Department of Zoology, University of Washington, Seattle, WA 98195-1800, United States","The Galapagos Penguin (Spheniscus mendiculus) population probably has always been small and largely restricted to the islands of Fernandina and Isabela. Counts suggest the current population of Galapagos Penguins is likely between 4,250 and 8,500, half of what it was in the early 1970s. Population size has varied and declined probably because of substantial changes in oceanic conditions. Body condition as evidenced by weight is enhanced during cold surface water conditions, La Nina, and deteriorates when surface waters are warmed, El Nino, and under the most severe conditions, penguins starve. Analysis of a long-term data set from counts of the population suggests that the population has fluctuated, dropping precipitously after the 1982-1983 El Nino and has since then been recovering very slowly. This parallels the overall warming in the Pacific during the last 20 years associated with the more frequent El Nino and less frequent La Nina events. These trends suggest that long-term global climate warming is likely to threaten the Galapagos Penguin population particularly because the population is small and its distribution restricted. New threats from climatic warming and increasing human perturbations such as fishing, inadvertent discharge of petroleum products, and transport of potential predators and pathogens to islands increase the risk of extinction.","El Nino; El Nino Southern Oscillation; Galapagos; Galapagos Penguins; Global climate change; La Nina; Population trends; Spheniscus mendiculus","Spheniscus mendiculus",,,,,,"Aebischer, N., Coulson, J., Colebrook, J.M., Parallel long-term trends across four marine trophic levels and weather (1990) Nature, 347, pp. 753-755; Allan, R., Lindesay, J., Parker, D., (1996) El Niño Southern Oscillation and Climatic Variability, , CSIRO, Collingwood, Australia; Barber, R.T., Chavez, F.P., Biological consequences of El Niño (1983) Science, 222, pp. 1203-1210; Bell, G.D., Halpert, M.S., Interseasonal and interannual variability: 1986 to 1993 (1995) NOAA Atlas No. 12, 12. , U.S. Government Printing Office 1195-386-626/37952, Washington, DC; Boersma, P.D., Adaptations of Galápagos Penguins for life in two different environments (1974) The Biology of Penguins, pp. 101-114. , B. Stonehouse [ed.], Macmillan, London; Boersma, P.D., (1974) The Galápagos Penguin: Adaptations for Life in an Unpredictable Environment, , Ph.D. diss., The Ohio State Univ., Columbus, OH; Boersma, P.D., An ecological and behavioral study of the Galápagos Penguin (1977) Living Bird, 15, pp. 43-93; Boersma, P.D., Galápagos Penguins as indicators of oceanographic conditions (1978) Science, 200, pp. 1481-1483; Boersma, P.D., Parrish, J.K., Flexible growth rates in Fork-tailed Storm-Petrels: A response to environmental variability (1998) Auk, 115, pp. 67-75; Cane, M.A., Oceanographic events during El Niño (1983) Science, 222, pp. 1189-1195; Graham, W.H., Simulation of recent global temperature trends (1995) Science, 267, pp. 666-671; Halpert, M.S., Ropelewski, C.F., Surface temperatures patterns associated with the Southern Oscillation (1992) J. Climate, 3, pp. 577-593; Harcourt, S., Report on the census of the Flightless Cormorant and Galápagos Penguin (1980) Noticias de Galápagos, 32, pp. 7-11; Harcourt, S., (1980) Report on the Census of the Flightless Cormorant (Nannopterum Harrisi) and Galápagos Penguin (Spheniscus Mendiculus) Around Fernandina and Isabela, , Unpubl. report, Charles Darwin Research Station, Ecuador; Merlen, G., The 1982-83 El Niño: Some of its consequences for Galá